History

The North American Bird Banding Program (NABBP), administered by the U.S. Geological Survey (USGS) Bird Banding Laboratory and the Canadian Wildlife Service's Bird Banding Office, uses standardized event types to categorize different bird banding activities.

For some context, bird banding in North America was first introduced in 1803 by John James Audubon, who tied silver wire around the legs of nestling eastern phoebes, two of which returned the following spring. Later on in 1882 Ernest Thompson Seton used printer's ink to mark snow buntings. In 1996, the North American Banding Council (NABC) was formed. Their mission was to train banders in safe, ethical practices of the capture and handling of wild birds (Wikipedia, 2021).

Motivation

Experts say that recent data suggests bird populations in North America have seen a loss of more than 1 in 4 birds since 1970. That's approximatelt 2.9 billion birds, a finding from the first-ever comprehensible assessment of the net population changes of birds in the United States and Canada (Cornell Lab of Ornithology, 2019). Some of the major reasons for this include, but is not limited to, habitat loss caused by agricultural intensification, urbanization, and climate change. 1 billion birds are found to die each year just from collision with windows alone, a direct result of increased urbanization (Ashburn, 2024).

This trend is happening amongst birds in every biome. Forest birds have seen a decline of 1 billion birds. Grassland birds have collectively declined around 53% or 720 million birds. What's more, the greatest losses are seen amongst the most common birds, from popular sights in bird feeders such as white-throated sparrows, to common sightings in nature, such as the red-winged blackbird. More than 90% if the overall losses are from just 12 families of common species, including sparrows, blackbirds, warblers, and finches (Cornell Lab of Ornithology, 2019).

As such, this project aims to see if bird migration patterns in North America between the 1970s and the 2010s, using data collected from the U.S. Geological Survey ScienceBase Catalog will show us a similar story, determining if bird banding is a useful tool in the analysis of bird trends caused by external factors such as agriculture expansion, urbanization, and climate change.

We focus on seven bird species selected for their diversity, abundance of records, and their grouping within the dataset:

  • Canada Goose
  • Wood Duck
  • Mourning Dove
  • Tree Swallow
  • Gray Catbird
  • American Goldfinch
  • White-throated Sparrow

To streamline the analysis, we retained only the data from 1970 and 2010, allowing for a clear comparison of migration patterns across these two decades. Each specie family in the dataset encompassed several species, so to main bias and to get a more streamlined overview, we chose to focus on one species from each family. Each of the chosen species furthermore has a good amount of data for analysis.

This website aim to understand the bird migration patterns changing in given time period and identify the number of banded birds are banded in banding events and their sub-divisons compare them with 1970s with 2010s.

Studies of bird migrations are important, banding in this century supports many other endeavors, including studies of avian behavior, ecology, and populations; preservation of endangered species; and regulating hunting of game species. In addition, banding activities provide information relevant to concerns for human health and safetyfor example, West Nile disease and bird strikes near airports. Results from banding studies support international conservation programs like Partners in Flight and the North American Waterfowl Management Plan. ref: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/North_American_Bird_Banding_Program.

Our goal for the end user is to gain information and awareness regarding the decline of birds in North America and how this is not just an isolated issue but rather a sign of wider ecological problems. To further this point we have attempted to make as many of our graphs interactive as possible, to facilitate an interesting learning environment and give the user some freedom of choice rather than making our website one hundred percent strictly linear.

Data Processing and Cleaning

To begin with data collection we used 7 csv files (groups 02, 04, 12, 28, 31, 39 and 44) from https://www.sciencebase.gov/catalog/item/653fa806d34ee4b6e05bc57d form 1960 to 2023. We started by merging the 7 files. To reduce the data size, we focused 1970s and 2010s decennies with focused 7 species by dropping the duplicates and keeping the less than 20% missing values features. We also removed the lines where the name of the specie was wrong.
Now, the final data set does not contains any the duplicates. However, it have some null values in few features. The Event date, Band Type, latitude and longitude features are cleaned for analysis.

def merge_data_files(list_files, output_file):

    df = pd.read_csv(list_files[0], on_bad_lines='skip')

    # Loop through the rest of the files and merge them into the DataFrame
    for file in list_files[1:]:
        new_df = pd.read_csv(file, on_bad_lines='skip')
        # Append the new DataFrame to the existing one
        df = pd.concat([df, new_df], ignore_index=True)

    # Save the merged DataFrame to a new CSV file
    df.to_csv(output_file, index=False)
In[]:
def process_data(input_file, output_file):
    # Read the input CSV file
    df = pd.read_csv(input_file)

    # Select years from 2010 to 2020 and from 1970 to 1980
    df = df[df['EVENT_YEAR'].between(
        2010, 2019) | df['EVENT_YEAR'].between(1970, 1979)]

    # Drop duplicates
    df = df.drop_duplicates()

    # Save the processed DataFrame to a new CSV file
    df.to_csv(output_file, index=False)
In[]:
def select_columns(input_file, threshold=20):
    # Read the input CSV file
    df = pd.read_csv(input_file)

    # Look at the percentage of missing values in each column
    missing_percentage = df.isnull().mean() * 100

    # Select columns with less than 20% missing values
    selected_columns = missing_percentage[missing_percentage < threshold].index.tolist(
    )

    print(
        f"Selected columns with less than {threshold}% missing values: {selected_columns}")

    return selected_columns
In[]:
def filter_columns(input_file, output_file, columns_to_keep):
    # Read the input CSV file
    df = pd.read_csv(input_file)

    # Filter the DataFrame to keep only the specified columns
    df = df[columns_to_keep]

    # Save the filtered DataFrame to a new CSV file
    df.to_csv(output_file, index=False)
In[]:
def filter_rows(input_file, output_file, column_name, value=None, nb_rows=100000):
    # Read the input CSV file
    df = pd.read_csv(input_file)

    # Filter the DataFrame to keep only rows where the specified column matches the value
    if value is not None:
        df = df[df[column_name] == value]
    else:
        # we keep only the value with more than nb_rows
        # Get the counts of each unique value in the specified column
        value_counts = df[column_name].value_counts()
        df = df[df[column_name].isin(
            value_counts[value_counts > nb_rows].index)]

    # Save the filtered DataFrame to a new CSV file
    df.to_csv(output_file, index=False)

def main():
    list_files = []
    for file in os.listdir('./data'):
        if file.endswith('.csv'):
            list_files.append(os.path.join('./data', file))

    output_file = "merged_data.csv"
    merge_data_files(list_files, output_file)

    process_data("merged_data.csv", "processed_data.csv")

    selected_columns = select_columns(
        "processed_data.csv")

    filter_columns("processed_data.csv", "final_data.csv", selected_columns)

    filter_rows("data/final_data.csv", "data/final_data.csv",
                "SPECIES_NAME", value=None, nb_rows=100000)
    print("Data processing completed. Merged and filtered data saved to final_data.csv")

df['Cl_EVENT_DATE'] = pd.to_datetime(df['EVENT_DATE'], errors='coerce')

# Filter rows with invalid dates
invalid_dates = df[df['Cl_EVENT_DATE'].isna()]

print("Invalid date entries:")
print(invalid_dates.count())

def fix_date(d):
    # Try swapping day and month
    try:
        return pd.to_datetime(d, format='%d/%m/%Y')
    except:
        return pd.NaT

# Try second attempt on invalid rows
df.loc[df['Cl_EVENT_DATE'].isna(), 'Cl_EVENT_DATE'] = df.loc[df['Cl_EVENT_DATE'].isna(), 'EVENT_DATE'].apply(fix_date)


df['Cl_EVENT_MONTH'] = df['Cl_EVENT_DATE'].dt.month.astype('Int64')

# 3) Extract the year as an integer
df['Cl_EVENT_YEAR'] = df['Cl_EVENT_DATE'].dt.year.astype('Int64')
df['Cl_EVENT_DAY'] = df['Cl_EVENT_DATE'].dt.day.astype('Int64')

# 4) Replace the original date column with the new one
df['EVENT_DATE'] = df['Cl_EVENT_DATE']
df['EVENT_MONTH'] = df['Cl_EVENT_MONTH']
df['EVENT_YEAR'] = df['Cl_EVENT_YEAR']
df['EVENT_DAY'] = df['Cl_EVENT_DAY']

# 5) Drop the temporary date columns
df.drop(columns=['Cl_EVENT_DATE', 'Cl_EVENT_MONTH',
                 'Cl_EVENT_YEAR', 'Cl_EVENT_DAY'], inplace=True)

Basic Statistics and general Data Analysis:

For the basic statistics, we chose to look at the bird banding event counts of each year in the two chosen decades to see if a trend is present. This was done in part to determine if our data would follow a similar pattern to expert findings, which it does, to see if it is even useful, and also to understand how these trends are evolving from a data perspective. For the maps, we chose to look at the overall geographical locations of banding for these species to again determine if our data followed a similar data to the experts' and then later use as a baseline for our migration analysis.

As for the data analysis, it was cruicial for us to refer to external sources to better understand our data and the implications of the real world on it. We learnt that bird banding is actually a pretty good indicator of the actual trends in bird population levels and migration patterns, which further underline the importance of such work. Furthermore, we also learnt how important birds are in understanding how nature in general is fairing.

The dataset contains 7 species with 23 features. Among the 7 species Canada Goose is the highest population with (1284279) and least bird is Tree Swallow. NABBP conducted 2 types of events B:Banding and E: Encounter where B indicates the initial banding event, where a bird is captured and a band is applied for the first time, E: Encounter represents a subsequent encounter with a previously banded bird. Encounters can occur through various means, such as recapture, resighting, or recovery. To band the species they used 25 different band types used based on their gender, age, size and location,among those band type 11 and 41 band types are mostly banded. Year with most bird banding events conducted: 1971. with Count: 299230 Year with fewest bird banding events: 1977 with Count: 175587. The most migrated countries are United States (US) and Canada (CA) in given period. Bird banding events are conducted several locations and they grouped to become a subdivions. The highest bird banding events conducted in Canada in Ontarion (CA-ON) and in US is New York (NY).Ontario is Canada's most populous province and a major location for bird banding activities due to its diverse habitats, including forests, wetlands, and large migratory corridors along the Great Lakes. New York is a key state for bird banding due to its strategic location along the Atlantic Flyway, a major migratory route for many bird species.

# For each species, plot the number of banding events by year

focus_species = df.SPECIES_NAME.unique().tolist()

n = len(focus_species)
n_cols = 2
n_rows = (n + n_cols - 1) // n_cols

fig, axes = plt.subplots(n_rows, n_cols, figsize=(20, 5 * n_rows), sharex=False)
fig.suptitle('Number of Banding Events by Year for Each Species', fontsize=25)
axes = axes.flatten()

for idx, species in enumerate(focus_species):
    ax = axes[idx]
    
    # 1) Filter and count
    counts = (
        df.loc[df['SPECIES_NAME'] == species, 'EVENT_YEAR']
          .value_counts()
          .sort_index()
    )
    
    # 2) Plot 
    if counts.empty:
        ax.text(0.5, 0.5, "No data", ha='center', va='center', fontsize=12, alpha=0.7)
    else:
        ax.bar(counts.index, counts.values)
        ax.set_xticks(counts.index)
    
    ax.set_title(species, fontsize=16)
    ax.tick_params(axis='x', rotation=90)
    ax.set_ylabel('Events', fontsize=14)
    ax.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)

# remove any extra axes
for ax in axes[n:]:
    fig.delaxes(ax)

# common X-axis label
fig.text(0.5, 0.04, 'Bird Band Event Year', ha='center', fontsize=20)

plt.tight_layout(rect=[0, 0.05, 1, 0.95])
plt.show()

    else:
        print(f"\n{species}: No data available.")

    axes[i, 0].set_title("Monthly", fontsize=16)
    axes[i, 0].tick_params(axis='both', labelsize=16)
    if i == 6:
        axes[i, 0].set_xlabel("Month", fontsize=14)
    axes[i, 0].set_ylabel(species, fontsize=16)

    # Plot 2: Seasonal
    axes[i, 1].bar(seasonal.index, seasonal.values, color='orange')
    axes[i, 1].set_title("Seasonal", fontsize=16)
    axes[i, 1].tick_params(axis='both', labelsize=16)
    if i == 6:
        axes[i, 1].set_xlabel("Season", fontsize=16)

    # Plot 3: Band type
    axes[i, 2].bar(band_type.index, band_type.values, color='green')
    axes[i, 2].set_title("Band Type", fontsize=16)
    axes[i, 2].tick_params(axis='both', labelsize=16)
    axes[i, 2].tick_params(axis='x', rotation=90)
    if i == 6:
        axes[i, 2].set_xlabel("Band Type", fontsize=16)

    # Plot 4: Event type
    axes[i, 3].bar(event_type.index, event_type.values, color='teal')
    axes[i, 3].set_title("Event Type", fontsize=16)
    axes[i, 3].tick_params(axis='both', labelsize=16)
    axes[i, 3].tick_params(axis='x', rotation=90)
    if i == 6:
        axes[i, 3].set_xlabel("Event Type", fontsize=16)

    # Plot 5: Subdivisions
    axes[i, 4].bar(subdivisions.index, subdivisions.values, color='purple')
    axes[i, 4].set_title("Top 5 Subdivisions", fontsize=16)
    axes[i, 4].tick_params(axis='both', labelsize=12)
    axes[i, 4].tick_params(axis='x', rotation=90)
    if i == 6:
        axes[i, 4].set_xlabel("Subdivision", fontsize=16)

plt.show()
